        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "Face-to-Face Learning",
          "Dropping out from a Program",
          "Graduated (0) vs Dropout (1)",
          "31071 Engineering sudents",
          "1 Engineering Program",
          "Student Demographics, Previous Academic Performance, Academic Information",
          "[Gender, Income (range), Access to Study Age, Student’ origins, Previous Studies, Admission score, TotalCredits1s, Attempts 1s]",
          "End of First Academic Year",
          "Data is collectedbetween 2010/2011 and 2015/2016.\n\nDataset is subsequently divided between early and late dropout and using different configurations:\n\n- Degree courses not considered\n\n- Courses considered as dummies\n\n- Courses considered as part of a multilevel model\n\nIn the last formulation, a random effects increment is added to the intercept to account for the probability of a course contributing to dropout.",
          "Generalized Linear Model, Decision Tree, Random Forest",
          "Holdout Method (70/30)",
          "Early Dropout\n\n{AUC: 0.9615 - GLM-Nested, Accuracy: 0.9342 - DT Not Nested & Dummy, Sensitivity: 0.9004 -DT-Nested, Specificity: 0.9294 - RF Not Nested}\n\nLate Dropout\n\n{AUC: 0.9091 - GLM-Nested, Accuracy: 0.8851 - DT Not Nested, Sensitivity: 0.8118 -DT-Nested, Specificity: 0.9312 - DT Not Nested}",
          "Authors use 3 different configurations of models to perform 2 distinct classification tasks:\n\nLate Dropout vs Graduated,\n\nEearly Dropout vs Graduated\n\nFrom results, it becomesapparent that detecting early dropout is relatively easier since most early dropouts are justified either by poor performance from the get go - which may indicate some difficulty to adapt.",
          "- Holdout Method\n\n- No integration of Course Interaction Data\n\n- Only consider binary classification scenarios\n\n- Small number of algorithms considered\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
